{
  "text": "Patients with a history of T1Hg bladder cancer require close surveillance cystoscopy: typically every 3 months for 2 years Nepple and O'Donnell from the time of the index tumour, then every 6 months for 2 years in recurrence-free patients. Most tumour recurrences occur within the first year. Cytology in combination with cystoscopy is a valuable tool for following T1Hg bladder cancer and, in this setting, demonstrates a sensitivity and specificity of 50% to 60%. [CITATION_1] Abnormal cytology in the absence of a bladder lesion requires a re-evaluation as previously described. Other tests, such as florescence in situ hybridization, have shown promise but require further study. 37",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "28956654"
